  "@id": "ocp:sep/parenthood",
  "meta": {
    "title": "Parenthood and Procreation",
    "description": "The ethics of parenthood and procreation apply not only to daily acts of decision-making by parents and prospective procreators, but also to law, public policy, and medicine. Two recent social and technological shifts make this topic especially pressing. First, changing family demographics mean that children are increasingly reared in blended families, by single parents, or by same-sex partners, prompting questions of who should be considered a child's parent and what good parenting requires. Second, the development and proliferation of \"Assisted Reproductive Technology\" (ART) raises questions concerning access to the technology, its permissibility, and its use to enhance future children or prevent the birth of children with certain conditions. Recent debate in ethics and political philosophy has focused on the following questions: In the following entry, we divide these questions into three sequential stages: the ethics of procreation (creating a child), to which we devote two sections, and then becoming parents (acquiring parental rights and responsibilities) and being parents (holding and discharging parental rights and responsibilities).",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-11T09:30:57.634Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-11T09:30:57.634Z",
    "datePublished": "2012-01-25T13:00:00.000Z",
